itemSummaries.fullDescription:
After flourishing for 25 million years, honey­bees in recent years have for some reason started to find themselves poorly adapted to life on the blue planet. The problem of colony collapse is not so severe in Taiwan as in Europe or the Americas, but the number of beekeeping operations here has nevertheless dropped from a peak of more than 2,000 to less than 800 today. But, just as bees act as a vector for the pollination of plants, there are many beekeepers that continue to work their craft and, in the process, provide an invaluable service for others.


Huang Dong-ming, the proprietor of Bee Family in Yi­lan County’s Yuan­shan Township, is the fourth generation in a line of beekeepers. There was a time when he ran a small operation generating less than NT$200,000 in revenues per year, but business grew at a clip of better than 10% a year for many years running, and today he heads a sizable firm that boasts nine retail outlets and brings in NT$120 million annually.
